wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the angular-tailwind-app project. Explain its purpose as a personal finance tracker built with Angular and Tailwind CSS. Describe the core functionality including user authentication, dashboard visualization, transaction and category management, budget tracking, and reporting. Document the application architecture, highlighting component-based design, service layer for API interaction, and reactive data flow using RxJS. Include high-level diagrams illustrating component hierarchy and data flow. Provide a conceptual walkthrough of user workflows such as onboarding, daily usage, and profile management. Make this section accessible to beginners while offering technical depth for experienced developers to understand system context and integration points.

wiki_catalogs.name: Route Configuration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Angular route configuration defined in app.routes.ts. Explain the structure of the Routes array, including path definitions, component loading via dynamic imports (loadComponent), and the use of empty path routes for layout grouping. Detail the routing setup for both public and protected sections of the application, highlighting how the AuthLayoutComponent wraps authentication routes and LayoutComponent wraps protected routes. Cover the use of route redirections (empty path to /login and wildcard ** to /login), children routes for nested navigation, and parameterized routes (e.g., /transactions/edit/:id and /categories/edit/:id) for dynamic content loading. Provide examples from the codebase showing how lazy loading is implemented without separate modules, leveraging standalone components. Include best practices for route organization, performance implications of lazy loading, and debugging common routing issues such as incorrect path matching or failed component loading.

wiki_catalogs.name: Layout Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the LayoutComponent, which serves as the main UI shell container for the application. Explain its role in structuring the dashboard interface by composing Navbar, Sidebar, and Footer components. Document the template structure, CSS classes from Tailwind used for responsive layout, and how it integrates with Angular Router to render routed components in the main content area. Describe the use of @ContentChildren or structural directives if applicable, and how it manages visual hierarchy and spacing. Include examples of how feature modules like Dashboard or Transactions are rendered within this layout. Address responsive breakpoints, accessibility landmarks (e.g., <main>, <aside>), and performance considerations such as lazy-loaded content projection. Provide guidance on modifying the layout for new routes or role-based UI variations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Tailwind CSS Integration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the Tailwind CSS integration in the angular-tailwind-app. Explain how Tailwind is initialized and configured via tailwind.config.js, including the 'content' array for tree-shaking, theme extensions (colors, fonts, spacing), and any custom plugins or variants. Detail how Tailwind's utility-first classes are applied across components for rapid UI development. Describe the integration with Angular's build system through angular.json and how JIT or AOT mode is leveraged. Document best practices for using utility classes effectively without compromising maintainability, such as leveraging @apply for repeated patterns and avoiding over-nesting. Include examples from the codebase where Tailwind classes are used in components like dashboard cards or form elements. Address responsive design using Tailwind’s breakpoint prefixes and dark mode considerations if applicable. Provide troubleshooting tips for common issues like missing styles or purge problems in production builds.

wiki_catalogs.name: Service Architecture
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create architectural documentation for the service-based state management pattern in this Angular application. Explain how each domain-specific service (TransactionService, CategoryService, BudgetService, UserService) acts as a single source of truth and encapsulates business logic for its respective feature set. Detail the use of RxJS Observables to expose data streams and enable reactive updates across components. Document the dependency injection mechanism that allows services to be shared across components and modules. Describe the interaction between services and the central ApiService for HTTP communication, including request orchestration and error handling. Include patterns for caching, data synchronization, and loading state management using LoaderService. Provide best practices for service design, such as separation of concerns, reusability, and testability through mocking.

wiki_catalogs.name: API Service Implementation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive API documentation for the ApiService class that wraps Angular's HttpClient to centralize all backend communications. Detail its role in setting default headers (including Content-Type and Authorization via Bearer tokens), managing the base URL from API_CONFIG in constants.ts, and handling environment-specific endpoint configurations. Explain the implementation of CRUD methods using generics for type safety across different data models (Transaction, Category, Budget, User). Document how HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) are abstracted with error handling via catchError operator from RxJS, including user-friendly error message transformation. Include concrete examples from the codebase such as fetching transactions or updating a category. Address security practices like token injection and response sanitization, and performance considerations such as request optimization and potential caching strategies despite current lack of implementation.

wiki_catalogs.name: Email & Password Authentication
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for email and password authentication flow. Explain the implementation of login and signup components including reactive form validation, error handling, and UI feedback mechanisms. Document the AuthService methods for login() and signup() that communicate with the backend via ApiService. Include details on client-side input validation, password strength requirements, and response handling for success and error cases (e.g., invalid credentials, email already exists). Provide code examples showing form binding, submission handling, and navigation post-authentication. Address security considerations such as avoiding plaintext password exposure, using HTTPS, and secure error messaging. Describe integration with AuthGuard and router state transitions.

wiki_catalogs.name: Dashboard Data Cards
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the dashboard data card components: BalanceCard, IncomeCard, ExpenseCard, and TransactionCountCard. Explain their individual responsibilities in displaying key financial metrics and how they are composed within the DashboardComponent. Document input bindings, async data handling via observables from TransactionService and BudgetService, and formatting using CurrencyService. Include usage examples, responsive layout behavior with Tailwind CSS, and performance considerations for change detection. Address common issues such as null data states, loading indicators, and integration with the global loader service. Provide code snippets showing template integration and component logic.

wiki_catalogs.name: Transaction List Display
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the TransactionListComponent. Explain how the component fetches and displays a paginated list of transactions using TransactionService. Document the implementation of filtering by date range, category, and transaction type (income/expense), along with sorting capabilities. Describe the use of Angular's async pipe with Observables for reactive updates. Include examples of template logic for conditional styling and currency formatting via pipes. Address performance optimizations such as trackBy functions and virtual scrolling considerations. Provide guidance on extending the component with search functionality or export options. Troubleshoot common issues like empty state handling and loading state synchronization.

wiki_catalogs.name: Category List Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the CategoryListComponent that displays all user-defined transaction categories. Explain the component's implementation using Angular's *ngFor directive to render category items with visual indicators for active/inactive status. Document the integration with CategoryService to fetch and delete categories, including the use of confirmation modal via ConfirmationModalComponent before deletion. Describe the UI structure, responsive layout using Tailwind CSS, and event handling for edit and delete actions. Include examples of how status toggling is visually represented and how error states are handled during API calls. Address accessibility considerations and performance optimization for large category lists.

wiki_catalogs.name: Budget Service
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the BudgetService implementation. Thoroughly explain its methods for creating, updating, and retrieving budget records, including setBudget(), getBudget(), and calculateSpending(). Document how it integrates with the ApiService to communicate with the backend API using HTTP methods. Explain the service's role in calculating threshold percentages and determining alert status based on actual vs. budgeted amounts. Include examples of observable data flow using RxJS, error handling patterns, and integration with transaction data via TransactionService. Address common issues such as stale budget data, race conditions during updates, and synchronization across components. Provide code snippets showing service injection and usage in components.

wiki_catalogs.name: Profile View
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the ProfileViewComponent used to display user profile information. Explain the component's template structure, data binding with the User model, and integration with UserService for fetching profile data. Document the UI layout, responsive design considerations, and display of user attributes such as name, email, and profile picture. Include how the component handles loading states and error scenarios. Provide examples of how the view subscribes to user data observables and ensures data consistency with authentication state. Address accessibility features and performance optimizations for rendering user data.

wiki_catalogs.name: User Model
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive data model documentation for the User model. Detail each property including id, email, name, avatar, preferences, and security settings. Explain the role of the User interface in type safety across authentication, profile management, and API interactions. Document validation rules such as email format and required fields, default values for preferences, and business logic like two-factor authentication status. Provide examples of how the User model is instantiated from API responses and serialized for updates. Illustrate its relationship with other models such as Transactions and Budgets through ownership. Include guidance on extending the model for additional profile fields and ensuring backward compatibility.

wiki_catalogs.name: ApiService Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive API documentation for ApiService, the central HTTP client wrapper in the application. Document all public methods including get, post, put, delete, and their parameter signatures (endpoint, data, options). Explain how interceptors (LoaderInterceptor) integrate with this service for loading state management and authentication header injection. Detail error handling mechanisms, retry strategies, and timeout configurations. Include usage examples from components such as TransactionListComponent and CategoryService showing real-world invocation patterns. Describe the service's dependency on Angular's HttpClient and its role in the overall data flow architecture. Address security considerations like JWT token attachment and XSS protection. Provide guidance on extending ApiService for new endpoint types and best practices for type-safe responses using generics.

wiki_catalogs.name: Unit Testing Components
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for unit testing Angular components in the application. Explain the use of TestBed to configure and instantiate components, including how to declare dependencies, providers, and child components. Document the testing of component inputs, outputs, lifecycle hooks, and DOM manipulation. Include examples from the codebase such as `app.component.spec.ts` to demonstrate setup, fixture creation, change detection, and assertion patterns. Cover testing of template logic, event bindings, and conditional rendering using Jasmine's `expect`, `spyOn`, and `it` blocks. Address how async operations in templates are handled during tests and how to verify interactions with services via spies. Provide guidance on isolating components and mocking external dependencies.

wiki_catalogs.name: Build Process Configuration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the Angular build process in the finance tracking application. Explain the configuration in angular.json including build options, asset copying, styles processing, and environment-specific settings. Detail how Tailwind CSS is integrated and processed during the build via tailwind.config.js and styles.css. Document the role of TypeScript configuration (tsconfig.json) in compilation, module resolution, and strict type checking. Cover Angular CLI commands such as 'ng build', 'ng serve', and 'ng lint' as defined in package.json scripts. Explain production optimizations including Ahead-of-Time (AOT) compilation, tree-shaking, minification, and differential loading. Include guidance on customizing the build for different environments (development, staging, production) using environment files and configuration overrides. Provide troubleshooting tips for common build errors related to module resolution, missing dependencies, or CSS processing issues.

wiki_catalogs.name: Loader Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Loader component. Explain its purpose in providing visual feedback during HTTP requests via integration with LoaderInterceptor. Document how the loader's visibility is controlled through LoaderService observables and async pipe in the template. Describe the structural design using Angular's *ngIf and animation states for smooth appearance/disappearance. Include a practical example showing how any feature module can trigger the loader during API calls (e.g., during login or transaction submission). Address accessibility considerations such as ARIA live regions for screen readers, theming using Tailwind CSS utility classes, and responsiveness across device sizes. Provide troubleshooting guidance for common issues like loader not appearing or staying visible indefinitely due to unhandled observables. Recommend best practices for centralized loading states and avoiding race conditions.

wiki_catalogs.name: Technology Stack & Dependencies
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the technology stack of the angular-tailwind-app. Detail the use of Angular v17+ for component architecture, routing, and dependency injection. Explain Tailwind CSS integration for utility-first styling and responsive design. Cover TypeScript configuration via tsconfig.json and build tooling through Angular CLI (angular.json). List and describe key dependencies including RxJS for observables, Angular Router for navigation, and HttpClientModule for API communication. Include version compatibility, setup rationale, and configuration best practices. Provide examples of how these technologies interact within the codebase. Address performance implications and development experience benefits of the chosen stack.

wiki_catalogs.name: Navigation Guards
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the AuthGuard implementation and its integration with the Angular Router. Explain how the AuthGuard service intercepts navigation requests to protect routes based on user authentication state. Document the logic within AuthGuard that checks for valid authentication (e.g., JWT presence in localStorage or in-memory state) and determines whether to allow access or redirect to login. Describe the usage of the canActivate guard in route configurations, including how it's applied to both layout-level routes and individual protected routes. Highlight the role of route data (data: { requiresAuth: true/false }) in determining guard behavior for different route groups. Provide concrete examples from app.routes.ts showing how AuthGuard is used to differentiate between public (login, signup) and private (dashboard, transactions, profile) routes. Include guidance on extending the guard for role-based access control, handling asynchronous authentication checks, and testing guard logic with mocks. Address common issues such as infinite redirect loops and unauthenticated state persistence.

wiki_catalogs.name: Navbar Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop comprehensive documentation for the NavbarComponent, which provides top navigation across authenticated views. Detail its visual design using Tailwind CSS, including responsive behavior on mobile (hamburger menu, dropdowns). Explain the integration with Angular Router for navigation links and how it reflects current route state (active link highlighting). Document event handling for user profile interactions, notifications, and theme toggling if present. Describe input/output bindings used for communication with parent components or services (e.g., toggling sidebar). Include accessibility practices such as ARIA labels and keyboard navigation support. Provide code examples showing how to extend the navbar with new menu items or integrate user avatar dropdowns. Address common issues like z-index conflicts and mobile touch behavior.

wiki_catalogs.name: Component-Level SCSS Styling
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for component-level SCSS styling used in Angular components. Explain the role of encapsulated SCSS files (e.g., dashboard.component.scss, transaction-form.component.scss) in defining custom visual styles that go beyond utility classes. Cover Angular's view encapsulation strategies (Emulated, ShadowDom, None) and how they affect style scoping. Illustrate how SCSS features like nesting, variables, and mixins are used to enhance readability and reuse within component styles. Provide concrete examples from the codebase such as styling the income-expense-bar-chart or modal components where complex visuals require custom CSS. Discuss performance implications of global vs. component-scoped styles and strategies to avoid specificity conflicts when combining with Tailwind utilities. Include guidance on when to use SCSS versus Tailwind, and how to maintain consistency in visual design across the application. Address common issues like style bleed and solutions using ::ng-deep (with caveats) or CSS custom properties.

wiki_catalogs.name: Data Model Relationships
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive data model documentation for the core financial entities in this application. Detail the structure, properties, and relationships between User, Transaction, Category, and Budget models. Explain how the Transaction model references Category and User, and how Budget may relate to both User and Transaction data. Document data types, validation rules, and business logic embedded in the models. Include usage of constants from constants.ts for categorization (e.g., income vs expense types). Illustrate how these models are instantiated and transformed through service layers and used in component templates via async pipes. Provide examples of model instantiation, serialization, and state persistence patterns. Address data integrity considerations and model evolution strategies.

wiki_catalogs.name: Request Lifecycle & Interception
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed documentation for the request lifecycle management system using Angular's HttpInterceptor interface. Focus on loader.interceptor.ts which listens to HTTP events to control application-wide loading states. Explain how the interceptor injects the LoaderService to emit 'start' and 'stop' events during request initiation and completion, enabling UI components like the global loader to react accordingly. Document the event filtering logic that distinguishes between request start, response, and error events. Describe how this pattern decouples loading state management from individual components, promoting reusability and consistency. Provide examples of how the loader.component.ts consumes these events to display or hide the loading spinner. Address common issues such as multiple concurrent requests and how the interceptor manages incremental counting to prevent premature loader dismissal. Include performance implications and best practices for minimizing overhead in high-frequency API call scenarios.

wiki_catalogs.name: OAuth Integration (Google & GitHub)
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for OAuth authentication using Google and GitHub providers. Explain the AuthService implementation of signInWithGoogle() and signInWithGitHub() methods that initiate popup-based OAuth flows. Document the OAuth redirect handling via auth-callback component, including URL parsing, token extraction, and session setup. Cover the use of Firebase Auth or similar external SDKs if present, or the custom OAuth endpoint integration. Include configuration requirements for OAuth client IDs, redirect URIs, and environment variables. Provide examples of handling OAuth success and failure scenarios, including popup blocking issues and user cancellation. Discuss security aspects such as state parameter usage, token verification, and preventing CSRF attacks. Address cross-browser compatibility and mobile considerations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Dashboard Charts
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive documentation for the dashboard chart components: IncomeExpenseBarChart, BudgetExpenseChart, and ExpenseChart. Detail their implementation using Angular's reactive templates and data binding to visualize financial trends. Explain how chart data is aggregated from TransactionService and BudgetService, transformed via helper functions in shared/utils, and rendered in the template. Document integration with any charting library (if inferred), or describe custom SVG/d3-based rendering if applicable. Cover responsiveness, animation states, color schemes via Tailwind, and performance optimization for frequent data updates. Include examples of data input formats, error handling for empty datasets, and accessibility considerations for visualizations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Transaction Form Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the TransactionFormComponent. Explain the reactive form implementation using Angular FormBuilder with validation rules for amount, date, category, and description. Detail the integration with CategoryService to populate category dropdown with type-specific filtering (income vs expense). Document the form's dual mode behavior for creating new transactions and editing existing ones, including pre-filling logic and submission handling. Cover error handling during API calls and user feedback via NotificationService. Include examples of date picker integration and currency input formatting. Address accessibility considerations and mobile responsiveness. Provide best practices for form state management and preventing duplicate submissions.

wiki_catalogs.name: Category Form Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the CategoryFormComponent used to create and edit transaction categories. Document the reactive form implementation using Angular FormBuilder with validation rules for name (required) and type (income/expense). Explain the color selection interface and how it binds to the category model. Detail the component's logic for distinguishing between create and edit modes based on route parameters. Cover the submission flow, including API interaction via CategoryService, success/error notifications using NotificationService, and navigation after save. Include usage of shared components like the layout and navbar, and describe responsive behavior on different screen sizes. Provide code examples showing form initialization and handling of category data from the resolver or direct input.

wiki_catalogs.name: Budget Management Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the BudgetManagementComponent UI implementation. Describe its visual representation of budget progress using progress bars or charts, display of remaining amounts, and threshold alerts. Document input properties, event outputs, and interaction patterns with parent components. Explain how it subscribes to BudgetService observables to reflect real-time updates and integrates with transaction data to show current spending. Include usage examples with code snippets, styling via Tailwind CSS, and responsive design considerations. Cover common issues like rendering delays, incorrect progress calculations, and theme consistency.

wiki_catalogs.name: Profile Edit
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the ProfileEditComponent that enables users to update their personal information. Document the reactive form implementation, form validation rules, and handling of user input for fields like name, email, and password. Explain the integration with UserService for submitting updates and processing responses. Cover the password change workflow, including current password verification and confirmation. Detail any implementation of two-factor authentication setup or profile picture upload if present. Include error handling for duplicate emails, network failures, and validation errors. Provide code examples of form submission, success feedback, and cancellation behavior. Address responsive form layout and security practices for sensitive operations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Transaction Model
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive data model documentation for the Transaction model. Detail properties such as id, amount, type (income/expense), categoryId, date, description, and metadata. Explain the significance of each field in financial tracking, including precision handling for monetary values and timestamp formatting. Document validation rules like positive amount constraints and required category association. Describe the relationship between Transaction and Category models, including how type consistency is enforced. Provide examples of transaction creation, editing, and serialization in forms and API calls. wiki_catalogs.name: AuthService Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed documentation for AuthService, responsible for user authentication and session management. Document public methods including login, signup, logout, googleLogin, githubLogin, and isAuthenticated. Explain how tokens are stored (localStorage), validated, and refreshed. Detail the OAuth2 flow implementation for Google and GitHub providers, including popup handling and callback processing in AuthCallbackComponent. Describe integration with AuthGuard for route protection and interaction with ApiService for authenticated requests. Include examples of component-level usage in LoginComponent and SignupComponent. wiki_catalogs.name: Service Testing
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for testing Angular services using Jasmine and Karma. Explain how to instantiate services with their dependencies, particularly HttpClient via HttpClientTestingModule for mocking HTTP requests. Demonstrate the use of `jasmine.createSpyObj` to mock dependent services such as Router or NotificationService. Cover testing of observables, error handling in ApiService, and authentication state management in AuthService. Use real examples from the codebase to show how to test CRUD operations in TransactionService and CategoryService. Include patterns for testing async behavior, retry logic, and request interception. Address testing of stateful services and proper cleanup in `beforeEach` and `afterEach` hooks.

wiki_catalogs.name: Deployment Targets & Strategies
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for deploying the Angular application to various hosting platforms. Explain how the build output (dist folder) is structured and served statically. Cover deployment to Firebase, Netlify, Vercel, and GitHub Pages with step-by-step configuration including routing fallbacks using 404.html for client-side navigation. Detail Progressive Web App (PWA) capabilities enabled via ngsw-config.json and service worker registration in app.module.ts. Address common deployment issues such as base href misconfiguration, MIME type errors, and service worker update conflicts. Provide performance optimization tips for deployed applications including lazy loading, code splitting, and CDN usage.

wiki_catalogs.name: Confirmation Modal Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the ConfirmationModal component. Explain its role in prompting user confirmation before critical actions such as deleting a transaction or category. Document the @Input properties (e.g., message, title, confirmButtonText) and @Output events (onConfirm, onCancel) that enable customization from parent components. Illustrate with a code example how the modal is opened from the CategoryList or TransactionList component using a boolean toggle and event binding. Detail the implementation of keyboard support (Escape to cancel, Enter to confirm), ARIA attributes (role='dialog', aria-labelledby), and backdrop click dismissal. Cover styling via SCSS and responsive behavior on mobile devices. Recommend patterns for reusing the modal across features while maintaining clean component communication.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for testing Angular route guards, specifically AuthGuard in the application. Explain how to simulate router state and test canActivate logic under different authentication states (logged in vs. logged out). Demonstrate mocking of AuthService and Router within test suites to verify navigation decisions. Use `TestBed.inject` to retrieve guards and test their return values (boolean, observable, or UrlTree). Include examples of synchronous and asynchronous guard evaluations. Address testing edge cases such as expired tokens, redirect behavior, and integration with protected routes defined in app.routes.ts. Provide best practices for isolating guard logic and ensuring full code coverage.

wiki_catalogs.name: Routing & Navigation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the Angular Router configuration and navigation system. Document the route definitions in app.routes.ts including path, component, and canActivate guard usage. Explain the AuthGuard implementation that protects routes based on authentication state. Describe the routing module setup and lazy loading patterns if implemented. Detail navigation patterns including routerLink usage in templates and programmatic navigation via Router service. Cover route parameters, query parameters, and fragment handling. Include error handling for invalid routes (404) and redirect logic. Provide examples of protected vs public routes and how authentication state affects navigation flow.

wiki_catalogs.name: Shared UI Components
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create documentation for reusable shared UI components beyond the core layout: Loader, ConfirmationModal, and BudgetManagement. For each, explain purpose, usage context, and implementation details. Document Loader's integration with HTTP interceptors (LoaderInterceptor) and visibility logic. Describe ConfirmationModal's @Input/@Output API for customizable messages and action handling. Detail BudgetManagement's form controls and service interaction for setting thresholds. Include examples of how these components are invoked from feature modules using templates and TypeScript. Cover accessibility features (e.g., modal ARIA attributes), theming via SCSS or Tailwind, and responsiveness. Provide best practices for reusing and extending these components across the application.

wiki_catalogs.name: BudgetService Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive documentation for BudgetService, responsible for budget creation, tracking, and alerting. Document methods: getBudget, createBudget, updateBudget, deleteBudget, checkThreshold, and calculateRemainingAmount. Explain integration with TransactionService to monitor spending against budget limits. Detail how budget alerts are triggered and communicated to the dashboard components. Include usage examples in BudgetManagementComponent and dashboard charts. Describe the service's use of BudgetModel and date-based calculations for monthly budgets. Address edge cases like rollover budgets or multi-currency scenarios. Provide performance tips for frequent budget checks during transaction entry.

wiki_catalogs.name: HTTP Request Mocking
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive documentation for mocking HTTP requests in Angular tests using HttpClientTestingModule and HttpTestingController. Explain how to intercept outgoing requests, assert method types (GET, POST, etc.), validate request headers (including Authorization tokens), and respond with mock data or error statuses. Demonstrate end-to-end testing of ApiService methods that interact with external endpoints defined in constants.ts. Show how to verify URL construction, query parameters, and request body payloads. Include examples of testing error handling, retry mechanisms, and loading state updates triggered by HTTP calls. Address testing interceptors such as LoaderInterceptor for UI feedback during requests.

wiki_catalogs.name: Styling Strategy
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the styling architecture combining Tailwind CSS and SCSS. Explain the global styles in styles.css and how they integrate with Tailwind's utility classes. Document the Tailwind configuration in tailwind.config.js including theme customization, plugins, and content sources. Describe the component-level SCSS files and their role in custom styling that extends beyond utility classes. Cover responsive design implementation using Tailwind's breakpoint system. Include guidelines for writing maintainable styles, avoiding specificity conflicts, and ensuring visual consistency. Provide examples of complex component styling that combines both approaches effectively.

wiki_catalogs.name: UserService Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed documentation for UserService, which manages user profile data and settings. Document methods: getUserProfile, updateUserProfile, changePassword, enableTwoFactor, and uploadAvatar. Explain how the service integrates with AuthService for authentication context and ApiService for backend synchronization. Detail data flow to ProfileViewComponent and ProfileEditComponent, including form binding and update submission. Cover security aspects like password change validation and 2FA enrollment flows. Include examples of handling profile picture uploads and error states during profile updates. Address caching strategies for user data and synchronization across tabs or sessions.

wiki_catalogs.name: State Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create architectural documentation for the service-based state management pattern in this Angular application. Describe how services like TransactionService, CategoryService, and BudgetService act as single sources of truth for their respective domains. Explain the use of RxJS Observables and Subjects for reactive data flow between components. Document the interaction between components and services via dependency injection. Cover state persistence using localStorage for authentication tokens and user preferences. Include patterns for error handling, loading states, and data synchronization. Provide best practices for service design, including separation of concerns and testability considerations.

wiki_catalogs.name: NotificationService Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create documentation for NotificationService, which handles in-app notifications and user alerts. Document public methods: show, success, error, warning, info, and clear. Explain the underlying mechanism (likely using a Subject/Observable pattern) for broadcasting messages to UI components. Describe integration with global layout components like Navbar or dedicated toast containers. Include usage examples from transaction submission, login failures, or budget threshold breaches. Address configuration options such as auto-dismiss timers, positioning, and theming via Tailwind CSS. Provide guidance on customizing notification types and handling accessibility requirements (screen readers, ARIA). Cover testing strategies for verifying notification triggers in component tests.

wiki_catalogs.name: API Integration Layer
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the ApiService that serves as the central HTTP client for backend communication. Document the wrapper around Angular's HttpClient with default headers, error handling, and base URL configuration from constants.ts. Explain the interceptor pattern used in loader.interceptor.ts to manage loading states during API calls. Detail request/response transformation, authentication header injection (Bearer tokens), and retry mechanisms. Cover endpoint organization, type safety with generics, and environment-specific API configuration. Include examples of CRUD operations for transactions, categories, and budgets. Address security considerations and performance optimization like caching strategies.

wiki_catalogs.name: LoaderService Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Document LoaderService, which manages application loading states and integrates with HTTP interceptors. Detail methods: show, hide, and isLoading observable. Explain how it works in conjunction with LoaderInterceptor to automatically display loading indicators during API requests. Describe integration with LoaderComponent for visual representation in the UI. Include examples of manual loading state control during complex operations like batch imports. Address race conditions in loading state management and best practices for ensuring loaders are always hidden after requests. Provide debugging tips for identifying 'stuck' loader states and performance considerations for minimizing UI blocking.

wiki_catalogs.name: Authentication System
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the authentication system including email/password login, signup, and OAuth integration. Document the AuthService implementation for token management, JWT handling, and user session persistence. Explain the login and signup component workflows with form validation and error handling. Detail the OAuth flow using Google and GitHub providers with popup authentication and the auth-callback component that processes redirect results. Cover security aspects like password hashing (client-side validation), token storage (localStorage), and session expiration. Include troubleshooting common authentication issues and best practices for secure implementation.

wiki_catalogs.name: CurrencyService Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create documentation for CurrencyService, which handles currency formatting, conversion, and locale-specific display. Document methods: format, convert, getSupportedCurrencies, and setDefaultCurrency. Explain integration with global application settings and user preferences stored in UserProfile. Detail usage in financial display components like BalanceCard, IncomeCard, and ExpenseCard. Include examples of formatting large numbers with appropriate separators and decimal precision. Address challenges with real-time currency conversion (if applicable) or offline mode considerations. Provide guidance on extending the service for additional currencies or integrating with external exchange rate APIs. Cover accessibility aspects of currency display for international users.

wiki_catalogs.name: Dashboard Components
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the dashboard feature and its component ecosystem. Describe the DashboardComponent as the main container and its composition of multiple data visualization components. Document each dashboard widget including BalanceCard, IncomeCard, ExpenseCard, TransactionCountCard, IncomeExpenseBarChart, and BudgetExpenseChart. Explain how these components receive data from services via async pipe and display real-time financial summaries. Cover chart implementation using any visualization library, data aggregation logic, and update mechanisms. Include responsive design considerations and performance optimization for rendering multiple charts simultaneously.

wiki_catalogs.name: Transaction Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the transaction management system. Document the TransactionService API for creating, reading, updating, and deleting transactions. Explain the TransactionListComponent implementation for displaying transactions with filtering, sorting, and pagination capabilities. Detail the TransactionFormComponent for creating and editing transactions with form validation and category selection. Cover the transaction data model, type enforcement (income/expense), and date handling. Include examples of error handling during submission and optimistic update patterns. Address performance considerations when handling large transaction datasets.

wiki_catalogs.name: Category Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the category management system that enables users to organize transactions. Document the CategoryService methods for CRUD operations and status toggling (active/inactive). Explain the CategoryListComponent implementation for displaying categories with edit/delete actions and status indicators. Detail the CategoryFormComponent for creating and updating categories with name, type, and color selection. Cover the category data model, validation rules, and integration with transaction creation. Include user experience considerations like confirmation dialogs for deletion and visual feedback for status changes.

wiki_catalogs.name: Budget Tracking
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the budget tracking functionality. Document the BudgetService API for setting budget limits, retrieving current spending, and calculating thresholds. Explain the BudgetManagementComponent implementation for displaying budget progress, alerts, and remaining amounts. Cover the budget data model including amount, period, and alert configuration. Detail the integration with transaction data to calculate actual spending against budgeted amounts. Include visualization of budget status and notification mechanisms when thresholds are exceeded. Address edge cases like recurring budgets and period rollovers.

wiki_catalogs.name: Reports Generation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the reports generation feature. Document the ReportsComponent implementation for aggregating transaction data by time periods (monthly, quarterly). Explain data processing logic for categorizing income and expenses, calculating totals, and generating visual summaries. Cover report export functionality including downloadable formats (PDF, CSV) if implemented. Detail the integration with charting libraries for visual representation of financial trends. Include performance considerations for processing large datasets and caching strategies for frequently accessed reports. Address user customization options for date ranges and report types.

wiki_catalogs.name: Profile Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the user profile management system. Document the ProfileViewComponent for displaying user information and ProfileEditComponent for updating personal details. Explain the UserService methods for retrieving and updating user data. Cover form validation, password change functionality, and two-factor authentication setup if implemented. Detail the integration with authentication state and profile picture handling. Include security considerations for sensitive operations and success/error feedback mechanisms. Address responsive design for profile forms and data persistence patterns.

wiki_catalogs.name: Data Models & Interfaces
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive data model documentation for all core entities in the application. Detail each model's structure, properties, and types including User (id, email, name, settings), Transaction (id, amount, type, category, date), Category (id, name, type, color, status), and Budget (id, amount, period, thresholds). Document relationships between models, such as transactions belonging to categories and users owning budgets. Explain validation rules, default values, and business logic embedded in the models. Include TypeScript interfaces and their role in ensuring type safety across the application. Provide examples of model instantiation and serialization patterns.

wiki_catalogs.name: Services Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive API documentation for all Angular services in the application. For each service (ApiService, AuthService, TransactionService, CategoryService, BudgetService, UserService, NotificationService, LoaderService, CurrencyService), document public methods, parameters, return types, and side effects. Include usage examples showing dependency injection and method calls from components. Explain the purpose and scope of each service, along with error handling patterns and observable lifecycle management. Cover service interactions and dependency chains. Address testing considerations and mock implementations for unit tests. Provide performance tips and anti-patterns to avoid when using these services.

wiki_catalogs.name: Testing Strategy
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the testing framework and strategy. Document the use of Jasmine and Karma (or Jest) for unit testing Angular components and services. Explain test structure including beforeEach, it, and expect patterns. Cover testing of components with TestBed, mocking of services using jasmine.createSpyObj, and HTTP request mocking with HttpClientTestingModule. Detail the testing of observables, async operations, and route guards. Include code coverage requirements and CI/CD integration. Provide examples of well-tested components and services from the codebase. Address end-to-end testing if implemented with Protractor or Cypress.

wiki_catalogs.name: Build & Deployment Pipeline
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the build process and deployment configuration. Document Angular CLI commands for development (ng serve), production build (ng build --prod), and linting (ng lint). Explain the configuration in angular.json including build options, asset copying, and environment-specific settings. Cover environment variable management through environment.ts files. Detail the production optimization features like Ahead-of-Time compilation, tree-shaking, and minification. Explain the Progressive Web App configuration via ngsw-config.json if service workers are enabled. Include deployment options to platforms like Firebase, Netlify, or Vercel with necessary configuration steps.

<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis: Angular-Tailwind Finance Tracker

## 1. Project Introduction

The **Finance Tracker** application is a personal finance management tool built with Angular and Tailwind CSS. The core purpose of this application is to help users track their income, expenses, budgets, and financial categories through an intuitive dashboard
